<PB REF="71">
vnto iustificacio~ for euery one that beleueth. Once agayne, if saluacion commeth of grace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. xi</NOTE> than is it not o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> workes, elles were grace, no grace. But if it come of worckes, than is grace nothynge. All these sentences teache vs, that we are delyuered fro~ all our synnes by Christ &amp; his rygh|teousnes, &amp; not by our owne workes and deseruynges.</P>
<P>Moreouer S. Paule sayth, wha~ ye were dead thorowe synnes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Colos. ii. Rom. v. Ephe. ii.</NOTE> &amp; the vncircu~cision of the flesh, God quic|kened you with christ, &amp; forgaue vs all our synnes, &amp; put out the hande|wrytyng, that was agaynst vs con|tayned in the lawe wrytten, &amp; that hath he taken oute of the waye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gen. iii. Luke. xi. Ioan. xii.</NOTE> and fastened it to the crosse, &amp; hath spoy|led rule and power, and hath made a shewe of them openly, &amp; triumphed ouer them in hys owne person. God hathe forgyuen vs all oure synnes,
